name: Chris Burniske
tweet: After years of bashing or ignoring crypto in the hopes it would go away, TradGov is now recognizing the genie won‚Äôt go back in the bottle. And so now the race is on to control it, by ‚Äúfostering responsible innovation.‚Äù

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: But since this is about control, and cryptography eats at the control of incumbent institutions, there is little reason for them to ‚Äúencourage or promote it.‚Äù

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
The crypto movement doesn‚Äôt strictly need incumbent institutions like TradFi, TradGov, or Web 2.0.

Of course the support of those institutions, and their distribution channels, accelerates the adoption of crypto.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: At the base of ‚Äúcrypto‚Äù is a lot of cryptography that empowers the global population to safely create, custody, and transact information & assets at scale without the need for incumbent institutions.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
To foster is to ‚Äúencourage or promote the development of‚Äù ‚Äî with the internet, the US government did that. 

But with cryptography in the public domain, the US government has consistently been antagonistic. 

It‚Äôs about control, and cryptography eats at the government‚Äôs control.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
‚ÄúFostering responsible innovation‚Äù is classic government doublespeak. 

‚ÄúInnovation we control‚Äù is more to the point.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Joel and Brad are venture trained, while I‚Äôm public equities trained via @ARKInvest (we all learn from each other). 

And so this bear I have provided a lot of market commentary‚Äî unorthodox for a VC.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: There are venture scale opps in the liquids of crypto, and sometimes the opp is greatest there as private market valuations lag the liquids (like‚Ä¶ now).

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Placeholder is venture in structure through and through, but even we have a much larger long-only public markets practice than most realize.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: On selling: many of the best VCs are not the immediate dumpers retail thinks. If you really believe in something, just because you get liquidity doesn‚Äôt mean more returns aren‚Äôt available. Often, holding smartly w/ tranched selling yields the best result.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Locking up capital for a long time, whether VC or HF structured, implies lots of trust from the LPs, which is tough to earn (implies quality GPs)

Short lockups make raising capital easier, but‚Ä¶ easy come, easy go.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
A nuance: fund structures are getting unorthodox. 

There are funds in crypto that provide good venture support, that have a more HF structure. 

Typically notable GPs, strict gates and decent length lockups are a marker of these.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
As HFs get redemptions (which VCs in a closed-capital fund aren‚Äôt exposed to), they may also have to dump their positions at depressed prices to meet redemptions, making the bear even worse. 

Smart crypto native VCs would be buying in such a scenario, supporting their positions.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: A HF that didn‚Äôt hedge may have a disastrous high watermark that they can‚Äôt get back to for years (no bonuses for yrs), not to mention as their AUM shrinks so too do their mgmt fees, and so there‚Äôs a negative feedback loop of declining compensation and potentially depression.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Structure of compensation in HFs (eg, high watermarks) are important to understand too. 

While a VC won‚Äôt get paid much of a bonus in a year like ‚Äò22, they don‚Äôt have to struggle with a high watermark or declining mgmt fees to pay people to do the work that is vital in a bear.

name: Chris Burniske

An example of a thought amendment, I'd been thinking 2H '22 would be the bottom, but that was a sign of my own overzealousness.

While 2H '22 may give us our first bottom wick, 2023 is starting to look rougher than anticipated & so I'm starting to draw out my horizon & plan.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Twitter is ephemeral, who cares. 

I used to care too much. 

This also applies as we rise into a bull, and keeping your mind open to new entrants / coins.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Lastly, not letting any "public calls" trap your mind into sticking to those calls if the data starts to go against you.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: You may say, "Well, you're rich and have unlimited capital." Everyone has limited capital, and capital is very divisible. If you are disciplined, you could divide up a $100 position size in tranches similar to how I size up an 8-figure position.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: And if those insane lows are hit, I want to make sure I'm able to deploy chunks of capital as those are the most amazing buys in retrospect. One of the worst feelings is being tapped out at the bottom.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
For example, if something goes ~100x the year before, at least plot what that thing looks like 95% down from its peak. 

People will always tell you it's not possible from the vantage of a bull, but it never ceases to amaze how we grind our way down there or at least close.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Also, planning for shock scenarios, and making sure that you always save capital for those scenarios.

I even plot some tranches that I don't expect to have to use (they're greyed out in my spreadsheets), and the position size will be a little smaller if not hit.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Getting disciplined with tranches, where your average price will be w/ each tranche, what your position sizes will be in $ and % of network terms, what multiples and cash on cash that gives you at future price targets, all helps keep you focused, optimistic, and sane.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: I'm learning a better balance between FOMO and FOBI (fear of being in) each bear, and each time I'm more patient, but reflect that I can do with even more patience. Aging has a way of doing that for me, luckily üòÖ

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
There is also a sneaky tendency to deploy more capital at higher prices, and then as things get scary, reign in the amount of capital deployed. Work to at least make it even, and if you're really good, use more capital the lower we go. 

Requires careful observation of yourself.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
As a professional allocator in a venture structure I can't afford to miss, and believe the less costly mistake is nibbling a little expensive & then working my way down, rather than waiting too long & not getting position sizes full up.

Position sizing key & underappreciated.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Another learning would be to just give things *at least* 6 months once the parabolas are clearly broken. 

No action can be the best action, even if action feels productive and relieves restlessness. 

Or take the lightest action possible, just to prime the pump.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: And then, the race to the next evolution of modular blockchains will be upon us, hitting maturity in the back half of this decade. Some winning monolithic chains will adapt, proving the strength of their core teams and communities, others will go down as a couple cycle wonders.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: One way we‚Äôve verbalized this @placeholdervc is ‚Äúvertically integrated‚Äù (ie, monolithic) booms first as it has fewer moving pieces that need to come together, but is ultimately surpassed by the compounding innovation of ‚Äúthin pieces, loosely joined‚Äù (ie, modular).

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
That expansion will be big enough in user numbers so as to prove how some monolithic architectures definitively will not scale. 

But despite that proof, coin holders of the disproven are likely to still do v well.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
In the raging debate between monolithic and modular blockchains, it‚Äôs clear modular is the more elegant long-term scaling approach. 

That said, next expansion will be a hodgepodge of architectures, & monolithic is likely to be more mature, potentially taking greater user share.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
As an investor in these downturns, your job is to patiently support teams building quality systems capitalized by cryptoassets that will (hopefully) surpass their former ATHs. 

Pretty simple if you zoom out.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Take rising networks like $ATOM, $DOT & $SOL. At current prices:

$ATOM = 4x to ATH
$DOT = 5x to ATH
$SOL = 5x to ATH

At bottom call targets, these maybe hit 10x's back to ATHs.

If waiting all in cash for these, you have to ask, worth it to miss 5x's to perfectly nail 10x's?

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Take $BTC and $ETH. At current prices:

$BTC = 2.3x to ATH
$ETH = 2.4x to ATH

If 2017 ATHs become the bottom of this cycle:

$BTC = 3.4x to ATH
$ETH = 3.4x to ATH

If waiting all in cash for these, you have to ask, is it worth it to miss 2.3x's to perfectly nail 3.4x's?

name: Chris Burniske

tweet: For an investor able to operate in both public and private markets, there is always opportunity - you just have to know where to look.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: As an example, 2018 was the biggest venture investment year for crypto w/ hefty valuations (at that time), despite the public markets getting absolutely trashed.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Public markets are marked-to-market every second, whereas in private markets it happens once a quarter.

As a result, public markets react much more quickly to new information, whereas private markets lag.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
At the middleware and application layer, it's less clear that governance should be used for technical decisions, but more clear that it should be used for economic decisions that affect all token holders.

Leading us back to conclude: the purpose of a token is to govern the token

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: And while token-based governance is rudimentary right now, the capital-asset that capitalized the system holds the natural right to govern the system (same goes for equities).

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: (Or we could exist in a zero-profit world, which would also be interesting)

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Which takes us back to the token. If there's sufficient surplus -- in other words, user payments are materially more than the cost to run -- then token holders will want to decide how that surplus is spent.

Reinvested? Token buybacks? Dividends?

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
But ultimately, once the balance sheets are burned down, all protocols will need to find a way to satisfy the following simple equation:

User Payments >= Cost to Run

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Any token project gets a giant window of grace to figure its sustainability out because they create their own capital, often sitting on 8-10 figure balance sheets that take a while to burn down.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: It's clear to everyone that launching a token is a great way to turbocharge growth in the short term, but it's less clear how that growth can be sustained, and paid for, in the long term.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: While PoW-assets like $BTC have little to do with governance, and layer-1 PoS-assets like $ETH 2.0 have clear value-accrual models through the emerging economies they power, middleware protocols or applications-with-tokens are still defining their value models.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
The higher up the stack a token sits, the more the token is about governing the token. 

Counterintuitive? Absurd? Only if you think tokens are value-less üßµ

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:

@element_fi allows users to split the base asset of a *yield generating position* into 2 separate, fungible tokens: The Principal Token and the Yield Token.

Chris Burniske
tweet:
Sunblock good, sunscreen questionable. 

My skin would be fried if I didn‚Äôt use sunblock. Anyone that says otherwise is LARP-ing ‚òÄÔ∏è

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Sunblock (Zinc Oxide, Titanium Dioxide) does not get absorbed into your body. It leaves an opaque coat, like putting a T-shirt on your face, that then protects your skin from directly receiving the sun‚Äôs rays.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Sunscreen (lots of the chemicals ending in -ate) gets absorbed into your skin, which can be more cosmetically appealing, but then breaks down within your body ‚Äî sunscreen breaks down, not your skin, so you don‚Äôt turn red ‚Äî creating free radicals that *potentially* cause cancer.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Don‚Äôt know how this entered CT debate, but there‚Äôs a big diff between sunscreen & sunblock. 

As a lifelong surfer, I use sunblock (Zinc Oxide or Titanium Dioxide) religiously, and avoid sunscreen. 

People saying you shouldn‚Äôt put anything on your skin must not get out much.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: And so we'll learn... but it would be a shame to endorse the same social mistakes when we have an enabling new technology that can help protect us... from ourselves.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
But, a hierarchy drunk on wealth & power never lets go. 

And so the truth comes out eventually -- the internet accelerates the revealing of truth, one reason why society is waking up to rampant BS in our institutions.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Internally building concentrated hierarchies is tempting as a more paved path that has textbook models, and it's still possible to externally hoodwink the majority into thinking you're building a network (for a while).

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Making space for emergent outcomes, as networks do, allows for more complex problems to be solved. 

The world is facing a slew of complex problems, and our hierarchies are not cutting it.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
*Time-consistency* is key: consistency of ethos, pathos, & logos allows a network to attract its tribe, and all work towards the most desired emergent outcomes.

Well designed governance, which doesn't have to be a hierarchy, puts structure around this *deliberate process*

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Blockchains allow us to coordinate without concentrated hierarchies, though the incentives and rules behind such coordination take time to get right.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
For most of human history, we've been subjected to hierarchies for coordination.

In hierarchies, power concentrates & then corrupts, to the detriment of the majority. Always happens.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
"If they both achieve 'success,' why does it matter?"

It matters because 'success' is subjective.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
#Cryptonetworks are run by crypto-natives, people committed to decentralization of data, wealth & power for the good of all.

#Cryptohierarchies are often run by Web 2.0 or TradFi transplants. While some can make a full transformation, many remain blind to their cultural habits.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Many #cryptohierarchies are parading as #cryptonetworks, but the feel, intent, and distribution of such systems are far from that of a network.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
#Cryptonetworks = Deliberate process, emergent outcome.

#Cryptohierarchies = Deliberate outcome, deliberate process.

(h/t @fifthworldzach)

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Institutional capital staking behind a network's social signal can amplify the vision.

But for our future, we had better hope the winners are well-distributed by the time that scale staking is needed.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
With nascent networks, initial distribution defines key characteristics of who is attracted to that network.

It signals the likely path of the network's culture. 

As a network matures, with PoS we unavoidably need institutional-scale capital to stake behind the social signal.

tweet:
9/ @cjremus @ChainflowPOS is focused on lowering institutional extraction, and I know there are many other efforts (feel free to add them here). 

Values over value.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: 8/ Once a network is live, reward labor & consumers, not capital.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
8/ The dream here is for the everyday person to earn their wages, and store their capital, in cryptonetworks. 

But that requires limiting how extractive a large player can be with their capital. 

Mechanism design needs more work here.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: 7/ If your liquidity mining strategy is full of institutional investors to pump your numbers, then you‚Äôre missing the point.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
6/ As an early-stage investor, we help fund, design, and navigate the nascent stages of a network. 

We are a partner to the entrepreneurs.

But we know our role is as a 3-10 year placeholder, that should get diluted, eventually ceding our place to others.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
5/ @placeholdervc is constantly debating where institutions should be involved in governance and earning, within cryptonetworks. 

@mlphresearch wrote this brief reflection:  https://t.co/MLCy4bcZ3k

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
4/ Early-on, people I respect encouraged this type of mining, and this is no swipe at them.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: In the future, it‚Äôs likely DAO governance becomes more like Docker containers ‚Äî with coordination-legos allowing groups to use a variety of consensus rules according to the type of decision being made, ‚Äî stitching together complex decision trees & organizations.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Right now most forms of decentralized governance in crypto are like mainframes‚Äî rigid & heavy monoliths.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: By distributing the decision-making load, groups can more efficiently and sustainably make decisions.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Theoretically, a pod could have a 1 of N voting structure where only 1 member needs to vote for a decision to go through.

While likely only suitable for lower stakes or emergency scenarios, any voter knows they‚Äôre held accountable & so will vote according to the pod‚Äôs principles

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: In most cases, the mere threat of the stick is enough to get people to behave in line with a group‚Äôs principles.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
This isn‚Äôt too far from the philosophical diff between PoW and PoS.

PoW assumes everyone‚Äôs a bad actor and punishes them constantly by making them burn electricity.

PoS assumes everyone‚Äôs a good actor and only punishes them if they violate consensus rules (more efficient).

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
If someone doesn‚Äôt vote according to the pod‚Äôs constitution, they can be challenged & ejected. 

Assume good behavior to expedite things, then punish bad behavior as necessary.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Credit to @OrcaProtocol for getting me thinking about this more generally.

With Orca, one can parametrize a ‚Äúpod‚Äù such that there‚Äôs a min quorum, time limit for voting, time limit for challenging, and then decisions go through.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Watching some of the boutique investment DAOs ‚Äî which can out execute traditional investment firms due to lightweight gov structures üëÄ ‚Äî this distributed & accelerated decision-making is already possible in some contexts.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Perhaps we haven‚Äôt standardized the right forms of ‚Äúdistributed governance‚Äù that accelerate group decision-making through flexible consensus rules.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Right now it‚Äôs murmured that ‚Äúdecentralized governance‚Äù slows down decision-making.

What if that‚Äôs a temporary truth?

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: As an entrepreneur, the important thing to remember is that you get to decide what you think is the fairest distribution of the network you're creating, and then find investors who match those values.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
To hit this goal, insiders are allocated 20-33% of a network fully-diluted to get it off the ground. 

The permissionless public then receives 67-80% of the initially distributed supply.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: For @placeholdervc, the range of what we see as viable today and that would help society move forward into more equitable lands, is outsiders getting 2-4x of insiders.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: If a small group of insiders regularly take ~half of the fully-diluted upside (which is common), we‚Äôre seriously kneecapping the redistributive effects of this technology in order to make a handful of people obscenely rich.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: While ‚Äúfair distribution‚Äù is a normative judgment, it flows from what we see as a consensus belief within crypto: creating level playing-fields where everyone has a chance at financial sovereignty.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
For crypto, an original sin we regularly observe is insiders owning too much of systems that are marketed as public, egalitarian networks.

https://t.co/1azcIWfFJN

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: "Contributions to the squad are positive-sum. And in return for their contribution, members have access to an expanded set of opportunities, claims on future economic flows and guarantees backed by the group."

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: "Though dollars keep squads afloat, dialing up the financial infrastructure too soon can kill the vibe. The squad economy primarily yields non-monetary forms of value."

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
"Squads have little use for internal financial incentives. 

Instead, playful exchanges produce trust, reciprocity, and VIBES‚Äîthe ineffable group energy that squads value most. 

Accordingly, the core of squad production is the continuous production of the squad itself."

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
"Squads are woke to the empty neoliberal promises of gig-economy 'employment' and para-social personal brands. 

Squads value self-determination, not through individualism, but through collective maintenance and care for one another."

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: "Recent events have completely exposed the limits of individual agency, creating a powerful demand for squad-based forms of resiliency...today's emerging culture of group cohesion is driven equally by the social and financial precarity of urban life."

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
"With new plug-and-play financial tools, squads are becoming more economically and socially resilient.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: "Whether housemates or friends sharing a Discord group, squads allow social currency and financial capital to inter-convert, creating opportunities and group resiliency that would have been impossible to achieve alone."

name: Chris Burniske

@MisterBitty_ Lastly, do not underestimate how hard it is to sell your darlings.

If an asset gives you a 100x, that can be life-changing. 

By that time, it will have given your brain truckloads of chemicals that make it v hard to let go. 

But to keep yourself sane, you must let some go.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
@MisterBitty_ At the 80-100x levels, some people will exit entirely, others will choose to hold a fraction forever. 

Both work, just know that you'll want some fiat (or stable-ish, widely used MoE) eventually.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
@MisterBitty_ For example, take 2x your cost out at a 20x (leaving 18x), 4x your cost out at 40x. Then, from that 40x level you have a 6x locked-in, but 32x your cost still riding. 

At an 80x or 100x you could do similar things (if you have assets that hit those levels).

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: @MisterBitty_ It is near impossible to exit perfectly at the top, so do it at comfortable levels over time. Get comfortable with foregoing paper gains to protect your principal.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
@MisterBitty_ Control your risk and start taking profits (into stable, diversified from crypto, assets) in the mid-to-late stages of the next mania. 

Some cryptoassets are worth holding forever, but if you are 100% crypto now, maybe you should only be 50% crypto by the end of the next bull.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
@MisterBitty_ Meditate, exercise, and *listen* to your loved ones to stay grounded. 

If those don't ground you, tune what will ground you now. 

Don't get lost in screens, charts and CT all day.

Make sure to zoom out your perspective regularly.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Ground yourself now; speculation cycles have accompanied promising new technologies for hundreds of years.

While no one can quite control them, we can control how we react, present, educate, communicate & steward the space.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: These curves (commonly called AMMs) are the fastest, lowest-cost means to create deep liquidity around an asset that the world has ever had.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Anyone who knows both financial systems will admit to the superior foundation that blockchains represent. 

Otherwise, why would every major financial institution, consulting firm, and tech-giant have their own blockchain research and implementation arms?

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: There is only so much time and attention that the eight billion Homo sapiens on Earth have, and within that time and attention, only so much capital that can be dreamt up and justified.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: If you can see the track that these cypher-economies are on, then you will also see there‚Äôs going to be a long-term war for economic-share between cypher-economies and the meatspace+digital economies of today.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
Socio-economic institutions will choose to use cypher-infra for its global accessibility, resilience, cost-superiority, eventual functional-equivalence & novel services. 

Consumers will consume services from these networks, and their embedded institutions, for the same reasons.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Regardless of what happens with individual networks, financial services will be followed by a more nuanced build of various socio-economic institutions, all of which will rely upon this shared financial infrastructure.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
While both Bitcoin and Ethereum are decentralized and open-source, and part of the same movement, they are providing different components of the financial services that the cypher-space needs.

Their different "value-adds" will become more & more obvious with time.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: 21ST CENTURY SERVICES: A unified and global language for assets is what causes some to speak of Ethereum as a future global-settlement layer.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: 21ST CENTURY SERVICES: For a retail user, sending equities from one custodian to another in the meatspace+digital is at least a multi-day or multi-week affair, whereas on Ethereum that transfer would settle in less than ten minutes.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: 21ST CENTURY SERVICES: This stands in stark contrast to the meatspace+digital economies, where each asset class has its own exchanges, custodians and fiefdoms, all of which inject capital and time costs into the transfer between fiefdoms.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: 21ST CENTURY SERVICES: With Ethereum, and so obvious that it might be forgotten, all asset types (equities, bonds, cryptoassets, real-estate, virtual land, etc) speak the same language & so there is fluid exchange between every asset so long as markets exist.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
21ST CENTURY SERVICES: A person can now fit near-unlimited wealth in their pocket & access it from anywhere with internet. 

Allowing for the preservation of value through space & time is a sorely needed service for society‚Äôs 3rd millennium (Bitcoin on Mars, @elonmusk?)

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
21ST CENTURY SERVICES: One of the key value propositions of BTC -- an absolutely fixed supply -- is novel in the credibility with which the Bitcoin network is able to enforce it. 

BTC‚Äôs commitment to fixed supply can be thought of as allowing it to preserve value through time.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: @jgonzales19701 Bitcoin is integrated throughout the piece: https://t.co/hRb5u2hooT

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
FUNCTIONAL EQUIVALENCE: Some will claim that because these cypher-systems are not yet functionally equivalent, they are a toy that will never get there, and should thus be disregarded. 

That would be a grave mistake, as it confuses an instance in time with the longer-term trend.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: FUNCTIONAL EQUIVALENCE: Functional equivalence as a pursuit is clear from the breadth and depth of talent that I have seen pour into the crypto space from Wall Street, Silicon Valley, and all parts of the globe over the last six years.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
FUNCTIONAL EQUIVALENCE: The rate at which permissionless financial services are popping up and iterating on Ethereum is mind-bending. 

And make no mistake, the DeFi community has functional equivalence as a north star that will be surpassed.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
COST-SUPERIORITY LEADS TO UNIT VOLUMES EXPLODINGüöÄüöÄüöÄ

Time and again, low-cost services have taken massive share within our economies. If you believe in the gospel of low-cost, then you better believe in the promise of cypher-space provisioned services over the long-run.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
COST-SUPERIORITY:  I expect the margins of these miners to look similar to electric utilities once BTC is fixed-supply, socially de-risked, and a massively used transactional network. 

This is a globally-set margin, for a globally-provided utility.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
COST-SUPERIORITY: Similar to Ethereum, users of Bitcoin are paying to access the commodity block-space of Bitcoin‚Äôs 21st century accounting system. 

There's a fee market for this access, where global miners have competitive pressures put on them to keep margins and fees low.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
COST-SUPERIORITY: One thing that helps the operators of services on Ethereum is their costs are also much lower. 

You can think of all the applications on top of Ethereum as sharing the capex & opex of the machines that run their operations, lowering the burden for each.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
COST-SUPERIORITY: When called, the user pays for the operations & the cost of these operations is set according to the complexity of the transaction for the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM). 

Costs that the consumer is charged are commodity costs, with hardly any margin added on.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: COST-SUPERIORITY: In this case, that software was built by Aragon and sent to Ethereum's ledger...While the software requires occasional maintenance, which does have associated costs, the ‚Äúdormant but live software‚Äù on Ethereum incurs zero operational cost until it is called.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: COST-SUPERIORITY: To use a deep dive example of crypto‚Äôs superior unit economics, it is now possible to run an organization that is functionally equivalent to an investment firm, enterprise, or sovereign democracy for ~$16 a month on Ethereum: https://t.co/WTjGh0rKJ2

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
In the vein of The Sovereign Individual, the lack of a military needed to keep cryptonetworks resilient & operating, is key to allowing these economies to operate at lower cost over time. 

They require less extraction, because they are lower cost to run & protect.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Together, these macro-and-micro resiliences make it such that no army is necessary to defend a cryptonetwork. Instead, the economics and nature of the network make it such that it is resilient to all attacks, by design.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
MICRO RESILIENCE: This is where public-key cryptography has been huge for protecting property, and digital creations, at low cost. Remote seizure is nearly impossible. 

Crypto is building protection-technology, and micro-resilience, into the fabric of online culture.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: MICRO RESILIENCE: On the micro-level, resilience to attack is important for the owner of any kind of property. Protecting property is critical to creation in the capitalist-geared world we live in.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: MACRO RESILIENCE: There has always been a fixation in crypto on ensuring security budgets of base-layer hardware is sufficient to reliably maintain and append to ledgers at scale...we must protect against ‚Äúdouble-spends‚Äù that could erode trust in the accounting system.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
MACRO RESILIENCE: On the macro level, crypto‚Äôs financial system needs to be resilient to attacks of all kinds... 

‚ÄúGiven enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow,‚Äù and the open-source ethos of these softwares works to their security advantage over the long-run.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: GLOBAL AUDIENCE: Unlike companies that own or rent servers to provision their services, in cryptonetworks a global set of sovereign servers perform the work for the network based on economic merit.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: GLOBAL AUDIENCE: Unlike companies that seek users nation-state by nation-state, in cryptonetworks users are sought on a global basis from inception.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
While this cypher-financial system will ultimately arrive at functional equivalence with incumbent financial infrastructure, it will not stop there. 

The base is superior, and so too will the end products be.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
This cypher-financial system is targeting:

-a global audience
-macro-and-micro resilience
-cost-superiority
-services designed for the 21st century & beyond.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet:
While the other revolutionary technologies no doubt led to evolution within the existing financial system, none of them built an entirely new financial system from scratch. 

Instead, they remained reliant on existing financial systems, placing power in predictable hands.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: In the process of capitalizing itself into relevance, this boom of crypto capital has built a native financial system to account for its very own bootstrapping.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Cryptonetworks have capitalized themselves into relevance over the last ten+ years, with the space most notably reaching for the trillion dollar value mark in late 2017.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: We saw this with railroads, electricity, automobiles, computers and the Web, and crypto has been no different.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Speculation fuels capital growth, and with capital a group of people has resources to deploy towards a shared vision at scale.

name: Chris Burniske
tweet: Financial capital outpaces the installation of new technologies, in part because financial capital is responsible for speculating new technologies into existence.
